To create a button that can open files in Visual Studio 2017, you can use the Windows Forms Application project template available in Visual Studio. Here is an example of how to achieve this:

1. Open Visual Studio 2017 and create a new Windows Forms Application project.
2. Design your form in the Windows Forms Designer by adding a button control.
3. Double-click the button to generate a click event handler for it.
4. In the code-behind file (usually named Form1.cs), locate the event handler method for the button click.
5. Inside the event handler method, add the code to open the file dialog and allow the user to select a file:
```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    OpenFileDialog openFileDialog1 = new OpenFileDialog();
    if (openFileDialog1.ShowDialog() == DialogResult.OK)
    {
        // Get the selected file name
        string fileName = openFileDialog1.FileName;

        // Open the file using Visual Studio
        System.Diagnostics.Process.Start("devenv.exe", fileName);
    }
}
```
6. Additionally, you may need to add the following using statement at the top of your code file to include the required namespace:
```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;
```
7. Save your project and run it. Clicking the button will open a file dialog, allowing you to select a file. After selecting a file and clicking "Open," it will be opened in Visual Studio.

Note: This example assumes that Visual Studio is installed in its default location (including devenv.exe). If your Visual Studio installation is in a different location, you should update the path to devenv.exe accordingly.

To open a specific file from a hardcoded directory using a button in Visual Studio 2017, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a new Windows Forms Application project in Visual Studio 2017.
2. Drag and drop a button control onto your form design.
3. Double-click the button to generate a click event handler for it.
4. In the event handler method for the button click, add the code to open the file:
```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string filePath = @"C:\path\to\your\file.txt";

    // Open the file using Visual Studio
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start("devenv.exe", filePath);
}
```
5. Save your project and run it. When you click the button, it will open the file specified in the `filePath` variable using Visual Studio.

Make sure to replace `"C:\path\to\your\file.txt"` with the correct path to your file.

If you want to open a file that is located in the same directory as your program, you can use the `Application.StartupPath` property to retrieve the directory path of your application. Here's an updated example:

1. Create a new Windows Forms Application project in Visual Studio 2017.
2. Drag and drop a button control onto your form design.
3. Double-click the button to generate a click event handler for it.
4. In the event handler method for the button click, add the code to open the file:
```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string filePath = Path.Combine(Application.StartupPath, "filename.txt");

    // Open the file using Visual Studio
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start("devenv.exe", filePath);
}
```
5. Save your project and run it. When you click the button, it will open the file `"filename.txt"` located in the same directory as your program using Visual Studio.

Remember to replace `"filename.txt"` with the name of your desired file. This code will dynamically get the path of your application using `Application.StartupPath` and then combine it with the file name to form the complete file path.

If you want to open a file located in a specific folder relative to your program, you can use the `Path.Combine()` method to create the file path. Here's an updated example:

1. Create a new Windows Forms Application project in Visual Studio 2017.
2. Drag and drop a button control onto your form design.
3. Double-click the button to generate a click event handler for it.
4. In the event handler method for the button click, add the code to open the file:
```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string folderPath = @"C:\path\to\your\folder";
    string fileName = "filename.txt";
    string filePath = Path.Combine(folderPath, fileName);

    // Open the file using Visual Studio
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start("devenv.exe", filePath);
}
```
5. Save your project and run it. When you click the button, it will open the file `"filename.txt"` located in the specified `folderPath` using Visual Studio.

Replace `"C:\path\to\your\folder"` with the appropriate path to the folder where your file is located. Make sure to update `"filename.txt"` with the name of your desired file. The `Path.Combine()` method is used to combine the folder path and file name to create the complete file path.

Apologies for the confusion. To open a file located within your program's files rather than a fixed path like "C:\path\to\your\folder", you can leverage the `Application.StartupPath` property along with a relative path to the file within your project. Here's an updated example:

1. Create a new Windows Forms Application project in Visual Studio 2017.
2. Drag and drop a button control onto your form design.
3. Double-click the button to generate a click event handler for it.
4. In the event handler method for the button click, add the code to open the file:
```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string folderPath = Path.Combine(Application.StartupPath, "Files");
    string fileName = "filename.txt";
    string filePath = Path.Combine(folderPath, fileName);

    // Open the file using Visual Studio
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start("devenv.exe", filePath);
}
```
5. Save your project and run it. When you click the button, it will open the file `"filename.txt"` located within the "Files" folder relative to your project using Visual Studio.

Ensure that you have a folder named "Files" within your project, and place the desired file (`filename.txt` in this case) within that folder. Adjust the `fileName` variable as needed for your specific file. The `Path.Combine()` method is used to combine the folder path (`Application.StartupPath`) and file name to generate the complete file path.

To include a folder within your program's files and access the files within that folder, you need to add the folder to your project as a "Content" and "Copy Always" to ensure it gets copied to the output directory. Here's how you can achieve this:

1. Open your Visual Studio project.
2. Right-click on your project in the Solution Explorer and choose "Add" -> "Existing Item".
3. Browse to the folder you want to include in your program's files, select the folder, and click "Add".
4. Right-click on the newly added folder in the Solution Explorer and choose "Properties".
5. Set the "Copy to Output Directory" property to "Copy always". This will ensure that the folder and its contents get copied to the output directory during build.
6. In your code, you can use the `Application.StartupPath` property along with a relative path to access the files within the folder. Here's an example:

```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string folderPath = Path.Combine(Application.StartupPath, "YourFolderName");
    string fileName = "filename.txt";
    string filePath = Path.Combine(folderPath, fileName);

    // Open the file using Visual Studio
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start("devenv.exe", filePath);
}
```

Make sure to replace "YourFolderName" with the actual name of the folder you added to your project. Adjust the `fileName` variable as necessary for your specific file.

When you run your program and click the button, it will open the file `filename.txt` located within the specified folder in the program's files using Visual Studio.

