I apologize for the misunderstanding. To open the folder using the file manager (such as Windows File Explorer), you can use the `System.Diagnostics.Process.Start()` method with the folder path. Here's an example:

```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string folderPath = Path.Combine(Application.StartupPath, "YourFolderName");

    // Open the folder using the file manager
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start("explorer.exe", folderPath);
}
```

Make sure to replace "YourFolderName" with the actual name of the folder you created in your project.

Now, when you run your program and click the button, it will open the specified folder in the file manager (Windows File Explorer in this case).

To open an .exe file located in the folder you created within your project, you can use the `Process.Start()` method to execute the .exe file. Here's an example:

1. Assuming you have created a folder named "YourFolderName" within your project that contains the .exe file.
2. In your code, use the `Application.StartupPath` property along with the relative path to access the .exe file within the folder. Here's an example:

```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string folderPath = Path.Combine(Application.StartupPath, "YourFolderName");
    string exeName = "YourProgram.exe";
    string exePath = Path.Combine(folderPath, exeName);

    // Open the .exe file
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start(exePath);
}
```

Make sure to replace "YourFolderName" with the name of the folder you created within your project, and "YourProgram.exe" with the name of your .exe file.

When you run your program and click the button, it will open the specified .exe file located within the folder using the default associated program for .exe files on your system.

If you have a folder within the folder you created in your project and you want to open an .exe file located in that inner folder, you can adjust the code to include the additional folder path. Here's an example:

```csharp
private void button1_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string folderPath = Path.Combine(Application.StartupPath, "YourFolderName", "InnerFolderName");
    string exeName = "YourProgram.exe";
    string exePath = Path.Combine(folderPath, exeName);

    // Open the .exe file
    System.Diagnostics.Process.Start(exePath);
}
```

Make sure to replace "YourFolderName" with the name of the main folder you created in your project, "InnerFolderName" with the name of the inner folder, and "YourProgram.exe" with the name of your .exe file.

When you run your program and click the button, it will open the specified .exe file located within the inner folder of the main folder using the default associated program for .exe files on your system.
